        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Method",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Caramelise the onions",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Melt the butter in a wide, heavy saucepan over a medium-low heat. Add the onions and a pinch of salt. ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "Caramelise",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpedfj74000004v4lnvczz3u"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " them, stirring every few minutes, for 30 to 40 minutes until very soft, deep golden, and jammy.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Stir in the flour and cook for 2 minutes, stirring constantly, until it smells biscuity.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Build the gravy",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Pour in the red wine and stir to ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "deglaze",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmp73vlkc0001wwv4i1qpucp8"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " the pan. Let it bubble for 2 minutes.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Pour in the hot beef stock. Add the Worcestershire sauce, bay leaf, and thyme sprigs. Bring to a simmer and cook uncovered for 15 minutes until the gravy has thickened and is deeply savoury.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Remove the bay leaf and thyme. Taste and adjust salt. If the gravy is too thick, add a splash more stock; too thin, simmer for a few more minutes.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "troubleshooter",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              {
                "fix": "True caramelisation takes 30 to 40 minutes over low heat. A quick brown is not the same thing.",
                "cause": "The heat was too high; the onions browned before they caramelised.",
                "symptom": "Onions are golden in 10 minutes and the gravy lacks depth"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Simmer uncovered for longer. The gravy should coat the back of a spoon.",
                "cause": "Not enough reduction after the stock was added.",
                "symptom": "Gravy is too thin"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Cook the flour with the onions for a full 2 minutes, stirring, until it smells nutty.",
                "cause": "The flour was not cooked long enough before the liquid went in.",
                "symptom": "Gravy is grainy or floury tasting"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Add a splash more Worcestershire sauce or a small splash of red wine vinegar to balance.",
                "cause": "The onions were cooked with sugar, or the stock was sweet.",
                "symptom": "Gravy is too sweet"
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Variations",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "For a red wine gravy built on roast pan drippings rather than caramelised onions, skip the onion stage and see the red wine gravy recipe. For a vegetarian version, use vegetable stock and replace the Worcestershire sauce with a splash of soy sauce.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Where this dish lives",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Onion gravy is the companion to bangers and mash more than to the Sunday joint, but it works with both. It is a working-class staple that became a comfort food across all income levels. It is cheap to make. Slowly cooked onions also produce one of the most satisfying smells in a kitchen.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    "servings": null,
